import Mathlib
import EvalTools.Markers
import LeanEval.GroupTheory.Defs.PCore

namespace LeanEval
namespace GroupTheory

open LeanEval.GroupTheory.Defs

/-!
# Baer–Suzuki theorem

Let `G` be a finite group, `p` a prime, and `x ∈ G`. Then `x` lies in the
`p`-core `O_p(G)` (the largest normal `p`-subgroup) if and only if for every
`g ∈ G`, the subgroup `⟨x, x^g⟩` generated by `x` and one of its conjugates
is a `p`-group.

The forward direction is immediate: `O_p(G)` is a normal `p`-subgroup and
contains every conjugate of any of its elements. The reverse direction is
the deep content — proved by Reinhold Baer (1958) for `p = 2` and by
Michio Suzuki (1965) in general. It is one of the standard tools for
extracting normal `p`-structure from local information about generating
pairs, and is used repeatedly in CFSG-era arguments together with the
Bender method and the signalizer functor theorem.

Note: hypothesising `IsPGroup p ⟨x, x^g⟩` for all `g`, specialised to
`g = 1`, forces `x` itself to be a `p`-element; we therefore do not state
that hypothesis separately.

The definition of `O_p(G)` used here is `Defs.pCore`, the supremum of all
normal `p`-subgroups of `G`.
-/

/-- **Baer–Suzuki theorem.** An element `x` of a finite group `G` lies in
the `p`-core `O_p(G)` iff every pair `(x, x^g)` of conjugates generates a
`p`-group. -/
@[eval_problem]
theorem baer_suzuki {G : Type*} [Group G] [Finite G]
    {p : ℕ} [Fact p.Prime] (x : G) :
    x ∈ pCore p G ↔
      ∀ g : G, IsPGroup p
        (Subgroup.closure ({x, g * x * g⁻¹} : Set G)) := by
  sorry

end GroupTheory
end LeanEval
